\section{Perfect complexes with cohomology of finite length}
\label{Section:4}
In Section~\ref{Section:5} we will work in the category of perfect complexes with finite length cohomology over a Noetherian local ring $R$ and for an endomorphism of finite length $\varphi\colon R\rightarrow R$ we will study relations between $h_{\mathrm{loc}}(\varphi)$  and $h_t(\mathbb{L}\varphi^\varstar)$, where $\mathbb{L}\varphi^\varstar$ is the total derived inverse image functor. Our goal in this section is to show that it makes sense to speak of $h_t(\mathbb{L}\varphi^\varstar)$. We have also collected a number of definitions and standard facts about the category of perfect complexes. The main references for this section are~\cite{SGA6,Thom,ThomTroba}.
\begin{definition} 
\label{Definition:4.1}
Let $R$ be a commutative ring and let $D(R)$ denote the derived category of the category of $R$-modules. A \emph{strictly perfect} complex on $R$ is a bounded complex of projective $R$-modules of finite type. The category of \emph{perfect} complexes over $R$, which we will denote by $D(R)_{\mathrm{perf}}$, is the full subcategory of $D(R)$ consisting of all complexes that are quasi-isomorphic to a strictly perfect complex on $R$. 
\end{definition}
The category $D(R)_{\mathrm{perf}}$ is a thick subcategory of $D(R)$, by~\cite[Expos\'e~I, Propositions~4.10, 4.17]{SGA6} or~\cite[Proposition~2.2.13]{ThomTroba}.
\begin{remark}
\label{Remark:4.2}
For definitions of strictly perfect complexes and perfect complexes on schemes see~\cite[Expos\'e~I, Definitions~2.1 and~4.7]{SGA6} or~\cite[Definitions~2.2.2 and~2.2.10]{ThomTroba}.
\end{remark}
Let $f\colon S\rightarrow R$ be a homomorphism of commutative rings. Denote the homotopy category of complexes of $S$-modules (respectively $R$-modules) by $\mathbf{K}(S)$ (respectively $\mathbf{K}(R)$). Let $f^\varstar\colon\mathbf{K}(S)\rightarrow\mathbf{K}(R)$ be the inverse image functor, that is, the functor that sends a complex of $S$-modules $E^\bullet$ to the complex of $R$-modules $E^\bullet\otimes_SR$. Let $\mathbb{L}f^\varstar\colon D(S)\rightarrow D(R)$ denote the total derived inverse image functor. Recall that $\mathbb{L}f^\varstar$ is an exact (triangulated) functor.
\begin{remark}
\label{Remark:4.3}
For a morphism $f\colon Y\rightarrow X$ of schemes, the total inverse image functor $\mathbb{L}f^\varstar$ was generally only defined as a functor $D^-(X)\rightarrow D^-(Y)$ in~\cite{SGA6} and~\cite[p.~99]{Hart}. Spaltenstein extended the definition of $\mathbb{L}f^\varstar$ to a functor $D(X)\rightarrow D(Y)$ in~\cite[Proposition~6.7]{Spalten}. Over an affine scheme, however, this will not make any difference because the category of perfect complexes over an affine scheme is equivalent to the
triangulated category obtained from the category of bounded chain complexes of finitely generated projective modules by inverting the quasi-isomorphisms.
\end{remark}
\begin{proposition}[{cf.~\cite[Expos\'e~I, Corollaire~4.19.1]{SGA6} or~\cite[p.~303, 2.5.1]{ThomTroba}}]
\label{Proposition:4.4}
Let $f\colon S\rightarrow R$ be a homomorphism of commutative rings and $\mathbb{L}f^\varstar\colon D(S)\rightarrow D(R)$ the total derived inverse image functor. Then $\mathbb{L}f^\varstar$ induces a functor  $D(S)_{\mathrm{perf}}\rightarrow D(R)_{\mathrm{perf}}$.
\end{proposition}
\begin{proof}
For $E^\bullet$ a strictly perfect complex of $S$-modules, $f^\varstar E^\bullet$ is clearly a strictly perfect complex of $R$-modules and this complex represents $\mathbb{L}f^\varstar E^\bullet$. Since (over an affine scheme) any perfect complex is (globally) quasi-isomorphic to a strictly perfect complex, the result follows immediately. 
\end{proof}
\begin{definition}[{cf.~\cite[Definition~3.2]{Thom}}]
\label{Definition:4.5}
Let $R$ be a commutative ring and $E^\bullet$ a complex of $R$-modules. The \emph{cohomological support} of $E^\bullet$ is the subspace ${\operatorname{Supph}}(E^\bullet)\subseteq{\operatorname{Spec}} R$ of those prime ideals $\mathfrak{p}\in{\operatorname{Spec}} R$ at which the complex $E_{\mathfrak{p}}^\bullet$ of $R_{\mathfrak{p}}$-modules is not acyclic.
\end{definition}
Thus ${\operatorname{Supph}}(E^\bullet)=\bigcup_{n\in\mathbb{Z}}{\operatorname{Supp}} H^n(E^\bullet)$ is the union of the supports in the classic
sense of the cohomology modules of $E^\bullet$.\par
Suppose now that $(R,\mathfrak{m})$ is a Noetherian \emph{local} ring and denote by $D_{\mathfrak{m}}(R)_{\mathrm{perf}}$ the full subcategory of $D(R)_{\mathrm{perf}}$ consisting of perfect complexes $E^\bullet$ with ${\operatorname{Supph}} E^\bullet\subseteq\{\mathfrak{m}\}$. Clearly a perfect complex $E^\bullet$ is in $D_{\mathfrak{m}}(R)_{\mathrm{perf}}$ if and only if $H^n(E^\bullet)$ is an $R$-module of finite length for every $n\in\mathbb{Z}$. The proof of the next proposition is straightforward.
\begin{proposition}[{cf.~\cite[Example~3.9.1]{Thom}}]
\label{Proposition:4.6}
Let $(R,\mathfrak{m})$ be a Noetherian \emph{local} ring. Then $D_{\mathfrak{m}}(R)_{\mathrm{perf}}$ is a thick subcategory of $D(R)_{\mathrm{perf}}$.
\end{proposition}
\begin{proposition}
\label{Proposition:4.7}
Let $f\colon(S,\mathfrak{n})\rightarrow(R,\mathfrak{m})$ be a homomorphism \emph{of finite length} of Noetherian local rings. Then the total derived inverse image functor $\mathbb{L}f^\varstar\colon D(S)_{\mathrm{perf}}\rightarrow D(R)_{\mathrm{perf}}$ (cf.~Proposition~\ref{Proposition:4.4}) induces an exact (triangulated) functor $D_{\mathfrak{n}}(S)_{\mathrm{perf}}\rightarrow D_{\mathfrak{m}}(R)_{\mathrm{perf}}$.
\end{proposition}
\begin{proof}
This statement quickly follows from the following more general fact proved in~\cite[Lemma~3.3]{Thom}: ``Let $X$ be a quasi-compact and quasi-separated scheme (e.g., an affine scheme). Let $E^\bullet$ be a perfect complex on $X$. If $Y$ is a quasi-compact and quasi-separated scheme and $f\colon Y\rightarrow X$ is a morphism of schemes, then ${\operatorname{Supph}}(\mathbb{L}f^\varstar E^\bullet)=f^{-1}({\operatorname{Supph}}(E^\bullet))$.'' Note that denoting by $^af$ the morphism ${\operatorname{Spec}} R\rightarrow{\operatorname{Spec}} S$ corresponding to the given homomorphism $f\colon S\rightarrow R$, we have $(^af)^{-1}(\{\mathfrak{n}\})=\{\mathfrak{m}\}$, as $f$ is assumed to be of finite length.
\end{proof}
Finally, we show that the category $D_{\mathfrak{m}}(R)_{\mathrm{perf}}$ has generators:
\begin{lemma}
\label{Lemma:4.8}
Let $(R,\mathfrak{m})$ be a Noetherian local ring. Then every nonzero object in $D_{\mathfrak{m}}(R)_{\mathrm{perf}}$ is a generator, in the sense defined in Section~\ref{Section:2}.
\end{lemma}
\begin{proof}
This statement quickly follows from Proposition~\ref{Proposition:4.6} and the following more general fact that was first proved in~\cite[Proof of Theorem~11]{Hop}. Also see~\cite[Lemma~1.2]{Neem0} or~\cite[Lemma~3.14]{Thom}: ``Let $R$ be a commutative Noetherian ring and let $E^\bullet, F^\bullet\in D(R)_{\mathrm{perf}}$ be two perfect complexes on $R$. Suppose that ${\operatorname{Supph}}(E^\bullet)\subseteq{\operatorname{Supph}}(F^\bullet)$. Then $E^\bullet$ is in the smallest thick subcategory of $D(R)_{\mathrm{perf}}$ containing $F^\bullet$.''
\end{proof}
In this section we have shown that the category $D_{\mathfrak{m}}(R)_{\mathrm{perf}}$ of perfect complexes with cohomology of finite length on a Noetherian local ring $(R,\mathfrak{m})$ is a triangulated category in which every nonzero object is a generator. Moreover, given an endomorphism of finite length $\varphi\colon R\rightarrow R$, the exact (triangulated) functor $\mathbb{L}\varphi^\varstar\colon D(R)\rightarrow D(R)$ induces an exact (triangulated) functor $\mathbb{L}\varphi^\varstar\colon D_{\mathfrak{m}}(R)_{\mathrm{perf}}\rightarrow D_{\mathfrak{m}}(R)_{\mathrm{perf}}$. Therefore, it makes sense to speak of $h_t(\mathbb{L}\varphi^\varstar)$ as defined in~Definition~\ref{Definition:2.3}.
