Let $\{x_1,\ldots,x_d\}$ be a regular system of parameters of $S$, $d=\dim S$, and let $y_i=\xi(x_i)$ for $1\leq i\leq d$. Let $G_S^{\bullet}(\underline{\mathbf{x}})$ and $G_R^{\bullet}(\underline{\mathbf{y}})$ be the Koszul complexs over $S$ and $R$, respectively, constructed from $x_1,\ldots,x_d$ and $y_1,\ldots,y_d$. The complexes $G_S^{\bullet}(\underline{\mathbf{x}})$ and $G_R^{\bullet}(\underline{\mathbf{y}})$ are generators for the triangulated categories $D_{\mathfrak{n}}(S)_{\mathrm{perf}}$ and $D_{\mathfrak{m}}(R)_{\mathrm{perf}}$, respectively. Since $\xi$ is a homomorphism of finite length, by Proposition~\ref{Proposition:4.7} the restriction of the total derived inverse image functor $\mathbb{L}\xi^{\varstar}\colon D(S)\rightarrow D(R)$ to $D_{\mathfrak{n}}(S)_{\mathrm{perf}}$ provides an exact (triangulated) functor $D_{\mathfrak{n}}(S)_{\mathrm{perf}}\rightarrow D_{\mathfrak{m}}(R)_{\mathrm{perf}}$. It is clear that $\mathbb{L}\xi^{\varstar}(G_S^{\bullet}(\underline{\mathbf{x}}))=G_R^{\bullet}(\underline{\mathbf{y}})$. Since $\xi\circ\psi=\varphi\circ\xi$, it follows that $\mathbb{L}\xi^{\varstar}\circ\mathbb{L}\psi^{\varstar}=\mathbb{L}\varphi^{\varstar}\circ\mathbb{L}\xi^{\varstar}$. Using Proposition~\ref{Proposition:2.2}, for any integer $n\geq1$ and any real number $t$ we obtain:
\begin{eqnarray*}
\delta_t\big(G_R^{\bullet}(\underline{\mathbf{y}}),\mathbb{L}{\varphi^n}^\varstar\left(G_R^{\bullet}(\underline{\mathbf{y}})\right)\big)&=&\delta_t\left(\mathbb{L}\xi^{\varstar}\left(G_S^{\bullet}(\underline{\mathbf{x}})\right),\mathbb{L}{\varphi^n}^{\varstar}\left(\mathbb{L}\xi^{\varstar}\left(G_S^{\bullet}(\underline{\mathbf{x}})\right)\right)\right)\\
&=&\delta_t\left(\mathbb{L}\xi^{\varstar}\left(G_S^{\bullet}(\underline{\mathbf{x}})\right),\mathbb{L}\xi^{\varstar}\left(\mathbb{L}{\psi^n}^{\varstar}\left(G_S^{\bullet}(\underline{\mathbf{x}})\right)\right)\right)\\
&\leq&\delta_t\left(G_S^{\bullet}(\underline{\mathbf{x}}),\mathbb{L}{\psi^n}^{\varstar}\left(G_S^{\bullet}(\underline{\mathbf{x}})\right)\right).
\end{eqnarray*}
By taking the logarithm, dividing by $n$, and passing to the limit as $n\rightarrow\infty$ we obtain $h_t(\mathbb{L}\varphi^{\varstar})\leq h_t(\mathbb{L}\psi^{\varstar})$. From Corollary~\ref{Corollary:5.2} and Theorem~\ref{Theorem:5.4} we get:
